    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-12-11T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-12-11T15:00:00-05:00" n="1143"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1143">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">760d.61/710: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Tittmann</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-12-11T21:00:00+01:00"
                            >December 11, 1939—9 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received December 11—6:16 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>317. The Finnish appeal was referred by the Assembly this afternoon to an <hi
                        rend="italic">ad hoc</hi> committee of 13 after an address by Holsti the
                    Finnish delegate, which will presumably be reported fully in the press. The
                    committee of 13 met after the Assembly and, on the basis of article XV,
                    paragraph 3 of the Covenant, despatched a telegram to the Russian
                        Government,<note n="23" xml:id="d1143fn23">The text of the telegram from
                        José Caeiro da Matta, the Portuguese Chairman of the Special Committee of
                        the Assembly, is in League of Nations, <hi rend="italic">Official
                            Journal</hi>, Nos. 11–12 (pt. II), November–December 1939, p. 529. For
                        the reply by Molotov, see telegram No. 1077, December 13, from the
                        Ambassador in the Soviet Union, <ref target="frus1933-39#pg_803">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, The Soviet Union, 1933–1939,
                            p. 803</ref>.</note> citing the Finnish appeal and requesting cessation
                    of hostilities with a view to negotiations.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Tittmann</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
